2023-05-11 14:16:12,478 INFO     ___FILE_ONLY___ [m[1mNAME[m
    gcloud topic startup - supplementary help for gcloud startup options

[m[1mDESCRIPTION[m
[m[1mChoosing a Python Interpreter[m

    The [1mgcloud[m CLI runs under Python. Note that [1mgcloud[m requires Python version
    3.5-3.9. Certain Windows and Linux installs include a bundled Python
    interpreter depending on the package and architecture. Similarly,
    Intel-based Macs offer the option to install CPython as part of the main
    install script. Otherwise, you must have a Python interpreter available on
    your system. The [1mgcloud[m CLI will attempt to locate an interpreter on your
    system PATH by looking for the following binaries:

      ▪ python3
      ▪ python

    If you have a bundled Python installed, it will be preferred. To override
    this you will need to set the [1mCLOUDSDK_PYTHON[m environment variable, see
    below.

    Other Python tools shipped in the Google Cloud CLI do not support Python 3
    and require Python 2.7.x, including:

      ▪ [1mdev_appserver[m

[m[1mBundled Python on Linux[m

    Linux-based installs include a bundled Python installation on x86_64
    architectures. This installation will be used by default. If you want to
    use a different Python installation, set the [1mCLOUDSDK_PYTHON[m environment
    variable to the absolute path to your python interpreter.

    If you have multiple Python interpreters available (including a bundled
    python) or if you don't have one on your PATH, you can specify which
    interpreter to use by setting the [1mCLOUDSDK_PYTHON[m environment variable. For
    example:

        # Use the python3 interpreter on your path
        $ export CLOUDSDK_PYTHON=python3

        # Use a python you have installed in a special location
        $ export CLOUDSDK_PYTHON=/usr/local/my-custom-python-install/python

    [1mgsutil[m versions 5.0 and onward support Python 3.5-3.8. To use a different
    interpreter for [1mgsutil[m than for the other Python tools, set the
    [1mCLOUDSDK_GSUTIL_PYTHON[m environment variable to the desired interpreter.

    [1mbq[m now supports Python 3.5-3.8. To use a different interpreter for [1mbq[m than
    or the other Python tools, you can set the desired interpreter by setting
    the [1mCLOUDSDK_BQ_PYTHON[m environment variable.

[m[1mConfiguring the Python Interpreter[m

    While not typically necessary, you are able to pass interpreter level
    arguments to the Python running [1mgcloud[m via the [1mCLOUDSDK_PYTHON_ARGS[m
    environment variable.

    A common use case for this (which has been special-cased) is to enable
    'site packages'. This allows Python to pick up libraries from the system (
    for example, those that may have been installed with [1mpip[m). Site packages
    may be necessary if you require certain native libraries (as is the case if
    you work with service accounts using a legacy [1m.p12[m key, for example). To
    enable site packages, set [1mCLOUDSDK_PYTHON_SITEPACKAGES=1[m. Note that
    enabling site packages may cause conflicts with [1mgcloud[m packaged libraries,
    depending on what you have installed on your system.

[m[1mSetting Configurations and Properties[m

    Your active configuration can also be set via the environment variable
    [1mCLOUDSDK_ACTIVE_CONFIG_NAME[m. This allows you to specify a certain
    configuration in a given terminal session without changing the global
    default configuration.

    In addition to being able to set them via [1mgcloud config set[m, each [1mgcloud[m
    property has a corresponding environment variable. They take the form:
    [1mCLOUDSDK_SECTION_PROPERTY[m. For example, if you wanted to change your active
    project for just one terminal you could run:

        $ export CLOUDSDK_CORE_PROJECT=my-project

    For more information, see [1mgcloud topic configurations[m.
